3. Step 1 — Start Lab Environment
Command:
lab start auth-review
Purpose:
•	prepares OpenShift cluster
•	resets authentication configuration
•	ensures API is reachable
________________________________________
4. Step 2 — Modify HTPasswd User File
File location:
~/DO280/labs/auth-review/tmp_users
HTPasswd file format:
username:hashedpassword
Example:
tester:$apr1$EyWSDib4$uLoUMpwohNWUrU5L5ogkB/
Passwords are hashed, not plain text.
________________________________________
5. Remove Analyst User
Command:
htpasswd -D ~/DO280/labs/auth-review/tmp_users analyst
Explanation:
Option	Meaning
-D	delete user
htpasswd	manage htpasswd files
Result:
Deleting password for user analyst
Now the analyst user is removed.
________________________________________
6. Update Passwords and Add Users
Command:
for NAME in tester leader new_admin new_developer ; \
do \
htpasswd -b ~/DO280/labs/auth-review/tmp_users ${NAME} 'L@bR3v!ew' ; \
done
Explanation:
This loop updates multiple users.
Part	Meaning
for NAME in	iterate users
htpasswd -b	batch mode
tmp_users	htpasswd file
password	L@bR3v!ew
Results:
Updating password for user tester
Updating password for user leader
Adding password for user new_admin
Adding password for user new_developer
________________________________________
7. Verify File
Command:
cat ~/DO280/labs/auth-review/tmp_users
Example output:
tester:$apr1$...
leader:$apr1$...
new_admin:$apr1$...
new_developer:$apr1$...
Meaning:
HTPasswd file ready
________________________________________
8. Login as Cluster Admin
Command:
oc login -u admin -p redhatocp https://api.ocp4.example.com:6443
Explanation:
Parameter	Meaning
oc login	authenticate to cluster
-u	username
-p	password
URL	API server
________________________________________
9. Create Secret for HTPasswd File
Command:
oc create secret generic auth-review \
--from-file htpasswd=/home/student/DO280/labs/auth-review/tmp_users \
-n openshift-config
Explanation:
Component	Meaning
secret	Kubernetes secret
auth-review	secret name
--from-file	load file
openshift-config	namespace used for cluster config
Result:
secret/auth-review created
________________________________________
10. Export OAuth Configuration
Command:
oc get oauth cluster -o yaml > ~/DO280/labs/auth-review/oauth.yaml
Explanation:
Option	Meaning
get oauth cluster	cluster authentication config
-o yaml	output YAML
| redirect to file |
________________________________________
11. Add HTPasswd Identity Provider
Edit file:
~/DO280/labs/auth-review/oauth.yaml
Add:
- htpasswd:
    fileData:
      name: auth-review
  mappingMethod: claim
  name: htpasswd
  type: HTPasswd
Explanation:
Field	Meaning
fileData	secret name
name	provider name
type	authentication type
mappingMethod	user mapping
________________________________________
12. Apply New Authentication Config
Command:
oc replace -f oauth.yaml
Explanation:
replace existing cluster authentication config
Result:
oauth.config.openshift.io/cluster replaced
________________________________________
13. Monitor Authentication Pods
Command:
watch oc get pods -n openshift-authentication
Explanation:
Part	Meaning
watch	repeat command
openshift-authentication	authentication namespace
Pods restart because authentication config changed.
Example:
oauth-openshift-xxxxx Running
________________________________________
14. Assign Cluster Admin Role
Command:
oc adm policy add-cluster-role-to-user cluster-admin new_admin
Explanation:
Part	Meaning
cluster-admin	highest privilege
new_admin	target user
Now:
new_admin = cluster administrator
________________________________________
15. Login as new_admin
oc login -u new_admin -p 'L@bR3v!ew'
Test privileges:
oc get nodes
Works because cluster-admin can access cluster resources.
Example:
master01 Ready control-plane
________________________________________
16. Test Limited User
Login as developer:
oc login -u new_developer -p 'L@bR3v!ew'
Try:
oc get nodes
Result:
Forbidden
Because developer does not have cluster role.
________________________________________
17. Disable Project Self Creation
Command:
oc adm policy remove-cluster-role-from-group \
self-provisioner system:authenticated:oauth
Explanation:
Default:
all users can create projects
After command:
only admins can create projects
________________________________________
18. Create Managers Group
oc adm groups new managers
Group created:
managers
________________________________________
19. Add Leader to Managers
oc adm groups add-users managers leader
Structure:
managers
   └ leader
________________________________________
20. Allow Managers to Create Projects
Command:
oc adm policy add-cluster-role-to-group \
self-provisioner managers
Meaning:
managers group can create projects
________________________________________
21. Leader Creates Project
Login:
oc login -u leader
Create project:
oc new-project auth-review
Important rule:
project creator automatically becomes project admin
________________________________________
22. Create Developers Group
oc adm groups new developers
Add user:
oc adm groups add-users developers new_developer
________________________________________
23. Give Developers Edit Access
oc policy add-role-to-group edit developers
Edit role allows:
create deployments
update services
delete resources
________________________________________
24. Create QA Group
oc adm groups new qa
Add tester:
oc adm groups add-users qa tester
________________________________________
25. Give QA Read Access
oc policy add-role-to-group view qa
QA can:
view pods
view deployments
view logs
QA cannot:
modify resources
delete resources
________________________________________
26. Final RBAC Structure
Cluster:
cluster-admin
   └ new_admin
Project: auth-review
leader → admin

developers group
    └ new_developer → edit role

qa group
    └ tester → view role
